Ayala, Bluescope Steel, Formosa, San Miguel: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-08-22T21:18:59Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-22/ayala-bluescope-steel-formosa-san-miguel-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Ayala Corp. (AC)  : The company bought back 280,000 shares
in the open market, a stock exchange filing showed. The stock
declined 2.2 percent to 308 pesos.  BlueScope Steel Ltd. (BSL)  : Australia’s largest
steelmaker aims to raise output capacity in  China  by 33 percent
to tap demand in the world’s biggest consumer, Paul O’Malley,
chief executive officer of the Melbourne-based company, said in
an interview. Bluescope dropped 5.7 percent to 74.5 Australian
cents.  DMCI Holdings Inc. (DMC)  : The largest Philippine
construction company will form a venture with Fluor Daniel Corp.
and AG&P to jointly bid for the construction of  Manila Electric
Co. (MER) ’s power plant project, a stock exchange filing showed. The
stock decreased 2.9 percent to 40 pesos.  Formosa Chemicals & Fibre Corp. (1326)  (1326 TT): Net income in
the first half climbed to NT$28.2 billion from NT$22.4 billion a
year earlier, the company said in a statement to the Taiwan
stock exchange. Formosa added 0.8 percent to NT$78.8.  Jinro Ltd. (000080)  (000080 KS): South Korea’s largest maker of
distilled liquor known as soju is considering an acquisition of
a distilled liquor factory in Japan, according to a regulatory
filing. The company hasn’t decided which factory to buy or the
price. Jinro declined 0.1 percent to 34,950 won.  MacroAsia Corp. (MAC)  : The Philippine provider of in-
flight services bought back 100,000 shares from the open market,
a stock exchange filing showed. The stock declined 4.6 percent
to 3.15 pesos.  San Miguel Corp. (SMC)  : The nation’s largest food and
drinks company may join a bid to convert the government’s
nuclear power plant in Bataan province, President Ramon Ang
said. The stock fell 1.4 percent to 122.90 pesos.  Towngas China Co. (1083 HK): The unit of Hong Kong’s oldest
utility said first-half net income rose to HK$302 million from
HK$172 million a year earlier. The shares dropped 1.7 percent to
HK$4.07.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anuchit Nguyen in Bangkok at 
 anguyen@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net . 